## Recipe 5: Process Map (Mermaid)

**Primary Role**: Analyst, Owner
**When to generate**: Always

### Recommended Structure

1. Diagram Type Declaration (swimlane / flowchart)
2. Mermaid Source Code
3. Color Legend
4. Reading Guide (how to interpret this specific diagram)

### Writing Tips

- Use `swimlane` (Mermaid `graph TD` with subgraphs) as default for processes with ≥ 3 roles.
- Use `flowchart` for single-role processes.
- Color semantics:
  - `#2d2d2d` — manual step
  - `#1a56db` — automated/system step
  - `#d97706` — decision point
  - `#dc2626` — exception path
  - `#7c3aed` — handoff to another process
- Step naming in diagram: use `S1`, `S2`, `S2.E`, etc. matching L1.4 IDs.
- Include start/end nodes explicitly.

### Tone Sample

```mermaid
graph TD
    START((Start)) --> S1
    S1[<b>S1</b><br/>Verify Refund<br/>Eligibility] --> D1{Within<br/>7 days?}
    D1 -->|Yes| S2
    D1 -->|No| S2_A
    S2[<b>S2</b><br/>Calculate Refund<br/>Amount] --> S3
    S2_A[<b>S2.A</b><br/>Manual Review<br/>by Team Lead] --> S3
    S3[<b>S3</b><br/>Process Refund<br/>in Stripe] --> S4
    S4[<b>S4</b><br/>Notify Customer<br/>via SMS] --> S5
    S5[<b>S5</b><br/>Close & Archive<br/>Ticket] --> END((End))

    style S1 fill:#2d2d2d,color:#fff
    style S2 fill:#2d2d2d,color:#fff
    style S3 fill:#1a56db,color:#fff
    style S4 fill:#1a56db,color:#fff
    style S5 fill:#2d2d2d,color:#fff
    style D1 fill:#d97706,color:#fff
    style S2_A fill:#dc2626,color:#fff
```

### Anti-Example (DO NOT DO THIS)

```
A → B → C → Done
```

**Why it's bad**: No step IDs, no role attribution, no decision points, no exception paths, no visual semantics.

